snippet.textDisplay:
For those who don't know the background of this poem/song..
It was written by the celebrated poet of the British occupied subcontinent, Iqbal. The first part of the poem, sung by the female singer, is called 'Shikwa' which literally means 'the complaint' which is basically the complaint of the frustrated Muslim of the colonial era, to God. 
When Iqbal wrote Shikwa, many religious figures of that time criticized this poem; Muslim is supposed to be grateful under any circumstances, hopelessness is a sin. I think fatwas were also issued against Iqbal. So Iqbal had to come up with 'Jawab-e-Shikwa', which means 'reply to the complaint'. It is supposed to be God's reply and here it is sung by the Qawals in the second part. The original poems are very long.
